{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508725"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:09:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:09:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11353"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11353"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.29,0.01,0.51,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"3998"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79068"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"3998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/3998"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11353"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64420"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1362"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3922"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4116"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27014"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79068"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old woman is referred to an Endocrinologist for further investigation of Cushing\u0027s syndrome diagnosed by her GP. Exogenous steroid intake by the patient has been excluded. Midnight salivary cortisol levels and a low-dose dexamethasone suppression test have confirmed hypercortisolaemia, and a plasma adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) level has returned at \u0026lt;5 pg/mL [10 - 60].\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MRI pituitary","High-dose dexamethasone suppression test","Inferior petrosal sinus sampling","CT adrenal glands","Corticotropin-releasing hormone test"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, hypercortisolism has been adequately demonstrated with two cross-confirmatory tests and a diagnosis of Cushing syndrome can be made. A plasma ACTH level is the next step to determine ACTH dependence, which helps distinguish between pituitary / ectopic ACTH-secreting tissue versus adrenal pathologies underlying the Cushing syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s suppressed ACTH level means their excess cortisol secretion is not being driven by a pathological over-production of ACTH (i.e., it is ACTH-\u003Cem\u003Eindependent\u003C/em\u003E), which instead is being suppressed through normal physiological negative feedback on the hypothalamic-pituitary axis. This localises the patient\u0027s problem to the adrenal gland(s) and imaging is indicated: first-line in this setting is a non-contrast \u003Cstrong\u003ECT adrenal glands\u003C/strong\u003E to identify either a focal hypersecretory adenoma or more diffuse nodular hyperplasia. Depending on the findings, adrenalectomy may be indicated to remove the hyperfunctioning tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epituitary MRI\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorticotropin-releasing hormone test\u003C/strong\u003E, and/or \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh-dose dexamethasone suppression test\u003C/strong\u003E help to localise ACTH-\u003Cem\u003Edependent\u003C/em\u003E disease to the pituitary gland. \u003Cstrong\u003EInferior petrosal sinus sampling\u003C/strong\u003E is performed when these tests return equivocal or discordant results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Once Cushing\u0027s syndrome is diagnosed, ACTH independence localises disease to the adrenal gland(s).","A suppressed ACTH level in the context of Cushing\u0027s syndrome suggests an adrenal source of excess cortisol production."],"references":["Nieman LK. Diagnosis of Cushing\u0027s Syndrome in the Modern Era. Endocrinol Metab Clin North Am. 2018;47(2):259-273. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29754631/","Barbot M, Zilio M, Scaroni C. Cushing\u0027s syndrome: Overview of clinical presentation, diagnostic tools and complications. Best Pract Res Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2020;34(2):101380. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32165101/","Uwaifo GI, Hura DE. Hypercortisolism. [Updated 2023 Jul 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551526/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64420"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11353"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64420"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T14:27:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T14:28:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"3998"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79068"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"positi